items.title: Segfault on process exit
items.body:
Hi,

After upgrading from qt4reactor==1.0 to latest master process starts to segfault on exit. Maybe you know what can cause that? I'm on OS X 10.9.4, reactor is installed this way: 

```
from qtreactor import pyqt4reactor as qt4reactor 
qt4reactor.install()
```

It only segfaults if some processing was done (http requests & responses, some work with QWebKit).

items.title: provide an easy way to install qt4reactor==1.0
items.body:
Hi,

`pip install qt4reactor==1.0` doesn't work:

```
pip install --download-cache qt4reactor==1.0 
Downloading/unpacking qt4reactor==1.0
  Could not find a version that satisfies the requirement qt4reactor==1.0 (from versions: 1.5, 1.6)
Cleaning up...
No distributions matching the version for qt4reactor==1.0
```

https://pypi.python.org/pypi/qt4reactor/1.0 incorrectly provides qt4reactor-1.5.tar.gz file.

It seems the only way to install qt4reactor==1.0 is to do that from source checkout like

`pip install -e git+https://github.com/ghtdak/qtreactor.git@0ccabebf54fa268c4110a7442a0c40a0fb57a5e5#egg=qt4reactor`.

It'd be great to have an easier way to do that because `qt4reactor >= 1.5` is backwards incompatible with "old" qt4reactor. Even imports are different - to be compatible with both something like

```
    try:
        from qtreactor import pyqt4reactor as qt4reactor
    except ImportError:
        import qt4reactor
```

is needed. 

It could make sense to call the release 2.0 because of these backwards incompatible changes (100% users must change their code to switch from "old" qt4reactor to "new")

Hello,

I'm using qt4reactor in a PyQt4 windows application. I'm using Python 2.6 and PyQt 4.5.4

I'm installing the reactor as follows:

```
   import qt4reactor
   app = QApplication(sys.argv)
   qt4reactor.install()

   # instantiate windows here

  from twisted.internet import reactor
  reactor.runReturn()
  sys.exit(app.exec_())
```

The problem I'm seeing is when I'm exiting the app (by closing the window), control doesn't immediately return to the shell. I have to hit Ctrl-C, then I get the following error:

```
QObject::killTimers: timers cannot be stopped from another thread
```

Then control returns to the shell.

From what I can gather I'm doing everything right.

Additionally, I've tried the following:

```
    def quit():
        app.quit()
        from twisted.internet import reactor
        reactor.stop()
        sys.exit()
    QtCore.QObject.connect(app, QtCore.SIGNAL("lastWindowClosed()"), quit)
```

and in the qt4reactor.py:

```
    def stop(self):
        super(QTReactor, self).stop()
        self._timer.stop()
```

With this combination I could sometimes exit cleanly but it's not consistent.
